Halve, then remove the core from the @green pepper{1} and chop into small 1 cm chunks. Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(stalks and all). Zest the @lime{1}. Roughly chop the @raisins{40%g}. Drain and rinse the @black beans{1} in a #colander{} under cold water.

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} over medium-high heat. Add the @British beef mince{120%g} and @British pork mince{120%g}. Cook until browned, breaking up with a #spoon{} as it cooks. This should take around ~{5-6%minutes}. If you get a lot of fat coming off the meat, simply spoon out and discard some of it. Once the mince is browned, add the pepper, @capers{15%g}, raisins, @ground cumin{2%tsp} and @dried oregano{1%tsp} and cook for ~{3%minutes} more.

Meanwhile, boil the @water{300%ml} in a #large saucepan{} over high heat. Stir in and dissolve half the @chicken stock powder{1} and then add the @basmati rice{150%g}. Cover with a #lid{} and leave to cook on a medium heat for ~{10%minutes}. After 10 mins, remove from the heat, add the black beans, pop the lid back and set aside for another ~{10%minutes}.

> TIP: The rice will finish cooking in its own steam.

Add the @tomatoes with onion and garlic{1}(finely chopped) and the remaining stock pot to the mince mixture. Pour in the @water{200%ml} and leave the sauce to simmer away on medium-high heat until thick and tomatoey, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Once the rice is cooked, stir in the lime zest, half the coriander and a good squeeze of lime juice. Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} as necessary.

When the sauce is nice and thick, remove from the heat, stir in the remaining coriander. Season with salt and pepper - remember the capers are quite salty, so taste it first! Spoon the rice into #bowls{} and top with the picadillo. Enjoy!